title: A Randomized Single and Multiple Dose Study Evaluating the Safety and Tolerability of RPh201 in Healthy Subjects and in Adults With Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This is a dual-centre, Phase I/IIa study, in healthy subjects and subjects with AD to investigate the safety, tolerability, cognitive, and behavioural effects of RPh201. The study will be divided into three parts: A, B, and C (NOT Performed)
description_detailed:
The primary objective of this study is to evaluate the safety and tolerability of RPh201 after single and multiple ascending doses. This study is designed with sufficient time in between dose escalations to allow for an interim analysis of safety and tolerability data as this is considered the safest approach to assess the effects of a compound with an undefined mechanism and therapeutic target.

This protocol is written with some flexibility to accommodate the inherent dynamic nature of Phase I clinical studies. Modifications to the dose, dosing regimen, and/or clinical or laboratory procedures currently outlined below may be required to achieve the scientific goals of the study objectives and/or to ensure appropriate safety monitoring of the study subjects. Interim safety analyses will guide dose escalation/reduction in the trial.

drug: RPh201 — a botanical drug product (5% w/w extract of gum mastic, resin of Pistacia lentiscus), formulated for subcutaneous administration
placebo: cottonseed oil (vehicle; placebo used in early studies)
explanation_target: Reason: RPh201 is described in preclinical and early clinical reports as a botany-derived extract with neuroprotective, neuroregenerative and neuroenhancing effects rather than a targeted anti-amyloid or anti-tau agent. citeturn0search1turn0search0

Act (trial intent): The referenced Phase I/IIa dual-centre study (NCT01513967) specifically evaluated safety, tolerability and the cognitive and behavioural effects of RPh201 in healthy subjects and adults with Alzheimer’s disease, indicating the trial aims included assessment of cognitive/functional effects. citeturn0search2
Act (formulation/placebo): Early human studies administered RPh201 subcutaneously in a cottonseed oil formulation and used cottonseed oil as placebo. citeturn0search1

Reflect: There is no indication RPh201 is a biologic (e.g., monoclonal antibody or vaccine) or a small‑molecule designed to target canonical AD pathologies (amyloid or tau); its described mode (botanical neuroenhancement/neuroregeneration) best matches the 'cognitive enhancer' category. citeturn0search1turn0search0

Support: RPh201 has shown functional/neuroenhancing effects in other settings (e.g., preclinical stroke models and clinical studies in optic neuropathy), consistent with a neuroenhancement/regenerative rather than a disease‑pathology specific mechanism. citeturn0search5turn0search7
explanation_agent: Reason: RPh201 is a botanical extract (gum mastic, Pistacia lentiscus) described in preclinical and early clinical reports as producing neuroprotective, neuroregenerative and neuroenhancing effects (promoting neurogenesis and synaptogenesis) rather than acting on canonical AD pathologies such as amyloid-beta or tau. citeturn0search3turn0search5

Act: The trial tests RPh201 as a cognitive enhancer / neuroenhancer (subcutaneous gum-mastic extract formulation). Given its described mechanism (neuroprotection, neuroregeneration, synaptogenesis) the most specific CADRO match is M) Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection. There is no clear single molecular target (e.g., amyloid, tau, ApoE) reported in the public preclinical/clinical literature. citeturn0search1turn0search5

Reflect: Classification as M is supported because the reported effects (neuronal differentiation, synaptogenesis, neuroprotection, functional cognitive improvement in models) align with synaptic plasticity/neuroprotective mechanisms. The literature and Phase 1/2a reports do not identify a canonical AD pathology target (A or B) nor a defined single biochemical target, so 'M' is more appropriate than A/B/I or R (multi-target). Safety/toxicology studies and clinical Phase‑1 details corroborate the botanical formulation and route (subcutaneous in cottonseed oil), reinforcing that this is a neuroenhancer/regenerative approach, not a disease‑pathology specific biologic. citeturn0search0turn0search2

Web search results (key sources consulted): 1) First‑in‑Human Phase 1 randomized SAD/MAD study of RPh201 (detailed description of formulation, neuroprotective/neuroenhancing rationale, Phase‑1 safety data). citeturn0search3turn0search1 2) Phase 2a randomized study in NAION describing mechanisms (neuronal differentiation, synaptogenesis, neuroprotection) and noting mechanisms are not fully known. citeturn0search5 3) Toxicity/toxicokinetic studies in rats and minipigs describing constituents (masticadienonic acid, isomasticadienonic acid), route (subcutaneous), and safety profile. citeturn0search0turn0search2 4) PubMed summary/abstract of phase 1 and preclinical background. citeturn0search9
